# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# GitHub contribution report - environment configuration
#
# Copy this file to ".env" and fill in your real Personal Access Tokens.
#   cp .env.example .env        (macOS/Linux)
#   Copy-Item .env.example .env (Windows PowerShell)
#
# The .env file is loaded automatically when python-dotenv is installed.
# Real environment variables always take precedence over .env values.
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Quick setup for one account
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Set your GitHub login and token, then run:
#   python github_report.py --user YOUR_LOGIN
#
GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_replace_with_your_token

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Multiple accounts (one token per account)
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Name each variable after the login it belongs to:
#
#   GITHUB_TOKEN_<LOGIN>   (login upper-cased, hyphens/dots become _)
#
# Examples:
#   GITHUB_TOKEN_ALICE=ghp_xxxx       → python github_report.py --user alice
#   GITHUB_TOKEN_BOB=ghp_xxxx         → python github_report.py --user bob
#   GITHUB_TOKEN_MYORG_BOT=ghp_xxxx   → python github_report.py --user myorg-bot
#
# You can also use numbered variables and list the matching logins explicitly:
#   GITHUB_TOKEN_1=ghp_xxxx           (add mapping in config.py DEFAULT_USER_TOKEN_ENV)

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IMPORTANT: token type decides what you can see
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# >>> USE A CLASSIC TOKEN (starts with "ghp_") WITH SCOPES: repo, read:org <<<
#
# Only a CLASSIC token with the "repo" scope can read:
#   * your own private repositories,
#   * PRIVATE repos owned by OTHER users where you are a collaborator
#     (this is the common "I committed to a private work repo" case), and
#   * private organization / work repositories (with "read:org").
#
# A FINE-GRAINED token (starts with "github_pat_") CANNOT see repositories
# owned by other users or organizations unless it was explicitly created for
# that owner and granted those repos. It is the usual reason work/private
# commits are missing from the report.
#
# For public-only reporting, "public_repo" + "read:org" is enough.
#
# Token scopes summary:
#   Full coverage  → classic with "repo" + "read:org"
#   Public only    → classic with "public_repo" + "read:org"
#   Avoid          → fine-grained token (misses collaborator/org repos)

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Optional: catch commits made with a work/personal email not on GitHub
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# If you committed to private/work repos with an email address that is NOT
# listed in your GitHub profile (Settings → Emails), those commits will be
# invisible to ?author=login queries and won't appear in the report.
#
# Fix option 1 (recommended): add the email to your GitHub profile.
#   GitHub Settings → Emails → Add email address → verify it.
#   Then re-run the tool — all past commits will appear automatically.
#
# Fix option 2: tell the tool to also search by that email address:
#   AUTHOR_EMAILS=work@company.com, personal@gmail.com
#   (Equivalent to the --author-email CLI flag)
#
# AUTHOR_EMAILS=work@company.com

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Optional: force-include specific repositories / organizations
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Comma- or space-separated. Useful for private/work repos that automatic
# discovery does not surface. (Equivalent to the --repo / --org CLI flags.)
# EXTRA_REPOS=acme/work-backend, acme/work-frontend
# EXTRA_ORGS=acme-corp, my-other-org
